  "prompt": "What is pork gelatin?",
  "response": "Pork gelatin is a type of gelatin derived from the collagen found in the skin, bones, and connective tissues of pigs. Collagen is a protein that, when processed (typically through boiling or enzymatic treatment), breaks down into gelatin. Pork gelatin is widely used in the food industry as a gelling agent, thickener, stabilizer, or emulsifier in products like gummy candies, desserts, marshmallows, yogurts, and certain processed foods. \n\nIt is also used in pharmaceuticals (e.g., in capsules) and cosmetics. Gelatin is valued for its ability to form a gel when mixed with water and heated, then cooled. Pork gelatin is distinct from other types of gelatin, such as bovine (from cows) or fish gelatin, and may be chosen based on dietary preferences, cultural practices, or religious restrictions (e.g., it is not kosher or halal). For those avoiding pork, alternative gelatins or plant-based substitutes like agar-agar or pectin are available.",
